ry:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Hancock County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:The Voice (franchise) contestants]]\n[[Category:Big Loud Records artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Lk95", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAs lead artist:update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgan_Wallen"}
{"title_page": "Closed Circuit (2013 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Closed Circuit\n| image          = Closed Circuit film.jpg\n| image_size     = 220px\n| border         = yes\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John Crowley (director)|John Crowley]]\n| producer       = [[Tim Bevan]]<br />[[Eric Fellner]]<br />Chris Clark\n| writer         = [[Steven Knight]]\n| starring       = [[Eric Bana]]<br />[[Rebecca Hall]]<br />[[Riz Ahmed]]<br />[[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]]<br />[[Jim Broadbent]]\n| music          = [[Joby Talbot]]\n| cinematography = [[Adriano Goldman]]\n| editing        = [[Lucia Zucchetti]]\n| studio         = [[Working Title Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] {{small|(UK)}}<br />[[Focus Features]] {{small|(US)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|08|28|US|2013|11|01|UK}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 96:20--><ref>{{cite web |title=''CLOSED CIRCUIT'' (15) |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/closed-circuit-film |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=September 19, 2013|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom<br />United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = $6.3 million<ref>{{cite web |title=''Closed Circuit'' (2013)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=closedcircuit.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=September 19, 2013 |accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=closedcircuit.htm |title=''Closed Circuit'' \u2013 International |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Closed Circuit''''' is a 2013 British-American [[Political cinema|political thriller]] [[drama film]] directed by [[John Crowley (director)|John Crowley]] and written by [[Steven Knight]], released on August 28, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title='Closed Circuit' Set For August 2013|url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/news/25340/-closed-circuit-set-for-august-2013|publisher=darkhorizons.com|accessdate=March 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053648/http://www.darkhorizons.com/news/25340/-closed-circuit-set-for-august-2013|archive-date=September 21, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The film stars [[Eric Bana]], [[Rebecca Hall]], [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]], [[Jim Broadbent]], and [[Riz Ahmed]].\n\n==Plot==\nA bomb planted in a lorry detonates in [[London]]'s [[Borough Market]] killing 120 people. The [[Metropolitan Police Service|London police]] receive an anonymous tip and arrest Farroukh Erdogan, a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] immigrant, as the terror cell leader and mastermind of the attack. Two other members of the cell die in the bombing and the fourth is killed by police in a shoot-out during the raid to apprehend him. When Erdogan's [[Barristers in England and Wales|Defense Barrister]] commits suicide, Martin Rose is appointed by the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] to replace him, joining [[Special Advocate]] Claudia Simmons-Howe. Due to national security concerns, Erdogan's case follows [[Justice and Security Act 2013|closed material procedures]]; Claudia represents Erdogan during closed sessions with a judge ruling what evidence is permissible for Martin to use in the open public trial. [[MI5]] Agent Nazrul Sharma is assigned to provide Claudia with the closed material and monitor her activities.\n\nMartin discovers that despite his extensive criminal record, Erdogan was somehow quickly approved for immigration from his previous residence in [[Germany]] to England and within six months was living well beyond his income. He finds proof that Farroukh Erdogan is really Mussi Kartal, a member of a terror cell responsible for bombing a [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] base in [[Munich]] a few years prior. Kartal cut a deal with prosecutors to avoid prison, agreeing to work as an [[informant]] for MI5 by infiltrating the London terror cell and providing MI5 with information to make arrests. Martin suspects that after the Borough Market bombing, MI5 feared their botched operation would be publicly blamed as directly financing terrorism and sought to have Kartal take the fall and suppress any evidence of MI5 involvement. Martin and Claudia discussed the matters discreetly during the [[England national football team]] match at the [[Wembley Stadium]].\n\nIn the first closed court session, MI5 Agent Melissa Fairbright reveals that Kartal's son Amir had hacked into his father's laptop and had provided valuable information to MI5. The judge orders Amir's testimony in court, deeming it relevant to the case. Amir, who is being monitored by MI5 agents at a [[safe house]] with his mother, manages to escape to his aunt's home. He meets with Martin and Claudia, giving them a [[USB flash drive|flash drive]] detailing his father's involvement with the MI5 terror cell operation. Martin and Claudia realize MI5 will kill Amir to protect themselves and go on the run with him overnight, planning to have him testify in court the next day. Amir testifies in closed session, but Kartal is later murdered in prison and made to look like a suicide by hanging. With Kartal dead, the case collapses and all evidence of the MI5 operation is suppressed from public disclosure. Amir and his mother, however, are allowed to remain in England.\n\nThree months later, as Martin and Claudia rekindle their romance that resulted in Martin's divorce from his wife, information of MI5's involvement in the Borough Market bombing is anonymously [[Leak (media)|leaked]] to the media.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Riz Ahmed]] as MI5 Agent Nazrul Sharma\n* [[Doug Allen (actor)|Doug Allen]] as Ryan\n* [[Eric Bana]] as Defense Barrister Martin Rose (named Vickers in earlier versions<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://events.accessatlanta.com/movies/closed-circuit-/M0-001-000047249-1#photos |title=Closed Circuit Showtimes, Info, Trailers, and Photos - Atlanta Calendar: Events, Festivals, Concerts |website=Events.accessatlanta.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref>)\n* [[Barbora Bobu\u013eov\u00e1]] as Piccola\n* [[Jim Broadbent]] as Attorney General of England and Wales\n* [[Kenneth Cranham]] as Cameron Fischer\n* [[Anne-Marie Duff]] as MI5 Agent Melissa Fairbright\n* [[Rebecca Hall]] as Special Advocate Claudia Simmons-Howe\n* [[Isaac Hempstead-Wright]] as Tom Rose\n* [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]] as Devlin\n* [[John Humphrys]] as himself\n* [[Denis Moschitto]] as Farroukh Erdogan/Mussi Kartal\n* [[Jemma Powell]] as Elizabeth\n* [[Julia Stiles]] as Joanna Reece\n* [[Angus Wright (actor)|Angus Wright]] as Andrew Altman\n* Luing Andrews as Belmarsh Guard\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Closed Circuit'' has received mixed reviews from critics. It currently holds a 43% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 134 reviews, with the critical consensus saying \"Slick and well acted, ''Closed Circuit'' unfortunately never quite works up a full head of steam, with a plot that's alternately predictable and full of holes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/closed_circuit_2013/ |title=Closed Circuit (2013) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> On another film aggregator, [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 50 (out of 100), based on 39 critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/closed-circuit |title=Closed Circuit |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.focusfeatures.com/closed_circuit}}\n* {{IMDb title|2218003|Closed Circuit}}\n* {{mojo title|closedcircuit|Closed Circuit}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|closed_circuit_2013|Closed Circuit}}\n* {{metacritic film|closed-circuit|Closed Circuit}}\n\n{{John Crowley (director)}}\n{{Steven Knight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Closed Circuit}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s political thriller films]]\n[[Category:British crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British political thriller films]]\n[[Category:British thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about murder]]\n[[Category:Films about security and surveillance]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Crowley]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Eric Fellner]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Tim Bevan]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:MI5 in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Steven Knight]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Closed Circuit\n| image          = Closed Circuit film.jpg\n| image_size     = 220px\n| border         = yes\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[John Crowley (director)|John Crowley]]\n| producer       = [[Tim Bevan]]<br />[[Eric Fellner]]<br />Chris Clark\n| writer         = [[Steven Knight]]\n| starring       = [[Eric Bana]]<br />[[Rebecca Hall]]<br />[[Riz Ahmed]]<br />[[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]]<br />[[Jim Broadbent]]\n| music          = [[Joby Talbot]]\n| cinematography = [[Adriano Goldman]]\n| editing        = [[Lucia Zucchetti]]\n| studio         = [[Working Title Films]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] {{small|(UK)}}<br />[[Focus Features]] {{small|(US)}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|08|28|US|2013|11|01|UK}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 96:20--><ref>{{cite web |title=''CLOSED CIRCUIT'' (15) |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/closed-circuit-film |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=September 19, 2013|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom<br />United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          = $6.3 million<ref>{{cite web |title=''Closed Circuit'' (2013)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=closedcircuit.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=September 19, 2013 |accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=closedcircuit.htm |title=''Closed Circuit'' \u2013 International |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Closed Circuit''''' is a 2013 British-American [[Political cinema|political thriller]] [[drama film]] directed by [[John Crowley (director)|John Crowley]] and written by [[Steven Knight]], released on August 28, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title='Closed Circuit' Set For August 2013|url=http://www.darkhorizons.com/news/25340/-closed-circuit-set-for-august-2013|publisher=darkhorizons.com|accessdate=March 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053648/http://www.darkhorizons.com/news/25340/-closed-circuit-set-for-august-2013|archive-date=September 21, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The film stars [[Eric Bana]], [[Rebecca Hall]], [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]], [[Jim Broadbent]], and [[Riz Ahmed]].\n\n==Plot==\nA bomb planted in a lorry detonates in [[London]]'s [[Borough Market]] killing 120 people. The [[Metropolitan Police Service|London police]] receive an anonymous tip and arrest Farroukh Erdogan, a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] immigrant, as the terror cell leader and mastermind of the attack. Two other members of the cell die in the bombing and the fourth is killed by police in a shoot-out during the raid to apprehend him. When Erdogan's [[Barristers in England and Wales|Defense Barrister]] commits suicide, Martin Rose is appointed by the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] to replace him, joining [[Special Advocate]] Claudia Simmons-Howe. Due to national security concerns, Erdogan's case follows [[Justice and Security Act 2013|closed material procedures]]; Claudia represents Erdogan during closed sessions with a judge ruling what evidence is permissible for Martin to use in the open public trial. [[MI5]] Agent Nazrul Sharma is assigned to provide Claudia with the closed material and monitor her activities.\n\nMartin discovers that despite his extensive criminal record, Erdogan was somehow quickly approved for immigration from his previous residence in [[Germany]] to England and within six months was living well beyond his income. He finds proof that Farroukh Erdogan is really Mussi Kartal, a member of a terror cell responsible for bombing a [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] base in [[Munich]] a few years prior. Kartal cut a deal with prosecutors to avoid prison, agreeing to work as an [[informant]] for MI5 by infiltrating the London terror cell and providing MI5 with information to make arrests. Martin suspects that after the Borough Market bombing, MI5 feared their botched operation would be publicly blamed as directly financing terrorism and sought to have Kartal take the fall and suppress any evidence of MI5 involvement. Martin and Claudia discussed the matters discreetly during the [[England national football team]] match at the [[Wembley Stadium]].\n\nIn the first closed court session, MI5 Agent Melissa Fairbright reveals that Kartal's son Amir had hacked into his father's laptop and had provided valuable information to MI5. The judge orders Amir's testimony in court, deeming it relevant to the case. Amir, who is being monitored by MI5 agents at a [[safe house]] with his mother, manages to escape to his aunt's home. He meets with Martin and Claudia, giving them a [[USB flash drive|flash drive]] detailing his father's involvement with the MI5 terror cell operation. Martin and Claudia realize MI5 will kill Amir to protect themselves and go on the run with him overnight, planning to have him testify in court the next day. Amir testifies in closed session, but Kartal is later murdered in prison and made to look like a suicide by hanging. With Kartal dead, the case collapses and all evidence of the MI5 operation is suppressed from public disclosure. Amir and his mother, however, are allowed to remain in England.\n\nThree months later, as Martin and Claudia rekindle their romance that resulted in Martin's divorce from his wife, information of MI5's involvement in the Borough Market bombing is anonymously [[Leak (media)|leaked]] to the media.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Riz Ahmed]] as MI5 Agent Nazrul Sharma\n* [[Doug Allen (actor)|Doug Allen]] as Ryan\n* [[Eric Bana]] as Defense Barrister Martin Rose (named Vickers in earlier versions<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://events.accessatlanta.com/movies/closed-circuit-/M0-001-000047249-1#photos |title=Closed Circuit Showtimes, Info, Trailers, and Photos - Atlanta Calendar: Events, Festivals, Concerts |website=Events.accessatlanta.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-01}}</ref>)\n* [[Barbora Bobu\u013eov\u00e1]] as Piccola\n* [[Jim Broadbent]] as Attorney General of England and Wales\n* [[Kenneth Cranham]] as Cameron Fischer\n* [[Anne-Marie Duff]] as MI5 Agent Melissa Fairbright\n* [[Rebecca Hall]] as Special Advocate Claudia Simmons-Howe\n* [[Isaac Hempstead-Wright]] as Tom Rose\n* [[Ciar\u00e1n Hinds]] as Devlin\n* [[John Humphrys]] as himself\n* [[Denis Moschitto]] as Farroukh Erdogan/Mussi Kartal\n* [[Jemma Powell]] as Elizabeth\n* [[Julia Stiles]] as Joanna Reece\n* [[Angus Wright (actor)|Angus Wright]] as Andrew Altman\n* Luing Andrews as Belmarsh Guard\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Closed Circuit'' has received mixed reviews from critics. It currently holds a 42% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 128 reviews, with the critical consensus saying \"Slick and well acted, ''Closed Circuit'' unfortunately never quite works up a full head of steam, with a plot that's alternately predictable and full of holes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/closed_circuit_2013/ |title=Closed Circuit (2013) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=July 26, 2015}}</ref> On another film aggregator, [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 50 (out of 100), based on 39 critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/closed-circuit |title=Closed Circuit |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=July 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.focusfeatures.com/closed_circuit}}\n* {{IMDb title|2218003|Closed Circuit}}\n* {{mojo title|closedcircuit|Closed Circuit}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|closed_circuit_2013|Closed Circuit}}\n* {{metacritic film|closed-circuit|Closed Circuit}}\n\n{{John Crowley (director)}}\n{{Steven Knight}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Closed Circuit}}\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s political thriller films]]\n[[Category:British crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British political thriller films]]\n[[Category:British thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about murder]]\n[[Category:Films about security and surveillance]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Films directed by John Crowley]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Eric Fellner]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Tim Bevan]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:MI5 in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Steven Knight]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:RT update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed_Circuit_(2013_film)"}
{"title_page": "Alvin Robertson", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Alvin Robertson\n| image           = \n| width           = \n| caption         = \n| position        = \n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 3\n| weight_lb       = 185\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1962|07|22}}\n| birth_place     = [[Barberton, Ohio]]\n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[Barberton High School (Barberton, Ohio)|Barberton]] (Barberton, Ohio)\n| college         = \n* [[Crowder College]] (1980\u20131981)\n* [[Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball|Arkansas]] (1981\u20131984)\n| draft_year      = 1984\n| draft_round     = 1\n| draft_pick      = 7\n| draft_team      = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| career_number   = 21, 3, 7\n| career_position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| career_start    = 1984\n| career_end      = 2000\n| years1          = {{nbay|1984|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1988|end}}\n| team1           = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1989|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1992|end}}\n| team2           = [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| years3          = {{nbay|1992|end}}\n| team3           = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years4          = {{nbay|1995|full=y}}\n| team4           = [[Toronto Raptors]]\n| years5          = 1996\u20131997\n| team5           = [[Florida Beach Dogs]]\n| years6          = 2000\n| team6           = San Antonio Bombers\n| highlights      = \n* 4\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|1986}}\u2013{{nasg|1988}}, {{nasg|1991}})\n* [[All-NBA Second Team]] ({{nbay|1985|end}})\n* [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|NBA Defensive Player of the Year]] ({{nbay|1985|end}})\n* 2\u00d7 [[NBA All-Defensive First Team]] ({{nbay|1986|end}}, {{nbay|1990|end}})\n* 4\u00d7 [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] ({{nbay|1985|end}}, {{nbay|1987|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1989|end}})\n* [[NBA Most Improved Player Award|NBA Most Improved Player]] ({{nbay|1985|end}})\n* 3\u00d7 [[List of National Basketball Association annual steals leaders|NBA steals leader]] ({{nbay|1985|end}}, {{nbay|1986|end}}, {{nbay|1990|end}})\n* Second-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[United Press International|UPI]] ([[1984 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1984]])\n* Third-team All-American \u2013 [[Associated Press|AP]] (1984)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 10,882 (14.0 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 4,066 (5.2 rpg)\n| stat3label      = [[Steal (basketball)|Steals]]\n| stat3value      = 2,112 (2.7 spg)\n| bbr             = roberal01\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry| {{flagu|United States}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]] | [[1984 United States men's Olympic basketball team|Team competition]]}}\n}}\n'''Alvin Cyrrale Robertson''' (born July 22, 1962) is an American retired [[basketball]] player who played in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) from 1984 to 1993, and for one final season in [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396]]. Robertson holds the record for the most steals per game played, averaging 2.71 steals per game for his career. He is the only guard in NBA history to have recorded a [[quadruple-double]].\n\n==Career==\nBest known for his defense, the 6'3\" Robertson played for ten years after being selected by the [[San Antonio Spurs]] with the seventh pick in the [[1984 NBA draft]] out of Crowder Junior College and the [[Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball|University of Arkansas]]. After five seasons with the Spurs, He finished out his career with the [[Milwaukee Bucks]], the [[Detroit Pistons]] and the [[Toronto Raptors]]. He also was a member of 1984 U.S. Olympic gold-medal team.\n\nIn 1986, Robertson became the inaugural winner of the [[NBA Most Improved Player Award]]. This also marked the first of four [[National Basketball Association All-Star Game]] appearances for the [[Basketball#Positions|guard]] (the others coming in 1987, 1988, and 1991). He also won the [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award]] in 1986,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/history/awards_defensiveplayer.html |title=Defensive Player of the Year |publisher=NBA.com |accessdate=April 21, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429054442/http://www.nba.com/history/awards_defensiveplayer.html |archivedate=April 29, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and led the league in [[steal (basketball)|steals]] in 1986, 1987 and 1991. Robertson still holds the top career steals-per-game average in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]], with 2.71 per contest over 779 career games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/history/records/regular_steals.html |title=Regular Season Records: Steals |publisher=NBA.com |accessdate=April 21, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070420123304/http://www.nba.com/history/records/regular_steals.html |archivedate=April 20, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nRobertson thrice led the league in steals. In 1985\u201386 he averaged a league-leading 3.7 steals per game,<ref name=\"spg leaders\">{{cite web |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/leaders/SPG_season.html |title=Season Leaders for Steals Per Game |publisher=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 21, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070312221406/http://basketball-reference.com/leaders/SPG_season.html| archivedate= March 12, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> a major factor in his earning the Defensive Player of the Year honor and being selected second-team All-NBA, one of only seven players in Spurs' history to have been selected first, second or third-team All-NBA. He was a four-time All-Star.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/basketball/nba/spurs/stories/MYSA020407.12C.BKNspurs.robertson.134a396.html |title=Top 30 NBA Spurs \u2014 No. 10: Alvin Robertson |last=Monroe |first=Mike |date=February 20, 2007 |publisher=MySA.com |accessdate=April 21, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210160248/http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/basketball/nba/spurs/stories/MYSA020407.12C.BKNspurs.robertson.134a396.html |archive-date=February 10, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nRobertson led the Spurs in steals four of the five seasons he was with the club, three times averaging more than three per game.<ref name=\"spg leaders\" /> Though he played only five seasons in San Antonio, he ranks third in club history in total steals, with 1,129. During his San Antonio days, he also recorded a steal in a then-NBA-record 105 consecutive games; [[Chris Paul]] surpassed it by recording a steal in 108 consecutive games from [[2006\u201307 NBA season|2007]] to [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Armstrong |first1=Jennifer |title=New Orleans Hornets' Chris Paul has steals streak stopped in dismal loss to Orlando Magic |url=http://blog.nola.com/hornetsbeat/2008/12/new_orleans_hornets_chris_paul_7.html |website=NOLA.com |accessdate=July 3, 2018 |date=December 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\nA multi-dimensional player, Robertson is one of only four NBA players to record a [[quadruple-double]] (double digits in four statistical categories in a single game) when he registered 20 points, 11 rebounds, 10 assists, and 10 steals while playing for the Spurs against the [[Phoenix Suns]] on {{Dts|1986|2|18}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/spurs/history/spurs_history.html |title=San Antonio Spurs History |publisher=spurs.com |accessdate=April 20, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070424140629/http://www.nba.com/spurs/history/spurs_history.html| archivedate= April 24, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> He is also the only non-[[Center (basketball)|center]] to record a quadruple-double, and the only player to do so with steals as the fourth category (the other three were with blocks).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/history/thurmond_741018.html |title=Nate Thurmond's Most MemoraBull Game |date=December 18, 2006 |accessdate=April 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1993\u201394 season, the [[Detroit Pistons]] traded Robertson to the [[Denver Nuggets]] in exchange for [[Mark Macon]] and [[Marcus Liberty]]. However, he never saw any playing time for the Nuggets due to pre-existing back injuries.<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/craig/draft/1994_draft/draft/13.html http://www.ibiblio.org/craig/draft/1994_draft/draft/13.html]. Retrieved on April 20, 2007.</ref>\n\nRobertson scored the first points in [[Toronto Raptors]]' history. [[Ed Pinckney]] won the franchise's opening tip-off against the [[New Jersey Nets]], Robertson hit a [[three-point field goal|three-pointer]], and the Raptors were ahead 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Basketball/NBA/Toronto/2004/10/31/694990.html |title=Constant change |last=Lankhof |first=Bill |publisher=SLAM! sports |accessdate=April 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|leader=y|record=y}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{Nbay|1984}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1984\u201385 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| 79 || 9 || 21.3 || .498 || .364 || .734 || 3.4 || 3.5 || 1.6 || 0.3 || 9.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{Nbay|1985}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1985\u201386 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| '''82''' || '''82''' || 35.1 || '''.514''' || .276 || '''.795''' || 6.3 || 5.5 || style=\"background:#E0CEF2;\"|'''3.7'''{{Double-dagger}} || 0.5 || 17.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{Nbay|1986}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1986\u201387 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio]]\n| 81 || 78 || 33.3 || .466 || .271 || .753 || 6.3 || 5.2 || style=\"background:#CFECEC;\"|3.2* || 0.4 || 17.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{Nbay|1987}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1987\u201388 San Antonio Spurs